{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Overfitting and underfitting describe two failure modes that determine whether a model will perform well on new data. Overfitting means the model memorized training noise; underfitting means it failed to capture the underlying pattern. Recognizing and correcting both is essential when training or fine-tuning any model in an agent pipeline."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 2 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "What it is" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Overfitting",
            "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " occurs when a model learns the training data too precisely — including random noise and outliers — and fails to generalize to unseen inputs. An overfit model has high training performance but significantly lower validation or test performance."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Underfitting",
            "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " occurs when a model is too simple to capture the patterns in the data. It performs poorly on both training and validation sets because it lacks the capacity to learn the underlying relationship."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The goal is to find the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "sweet spot",
            "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " — a model complex enough to capture real patterns but constrained enough to ignore noise."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 2 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "Why it matters" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "An overfit intent classifier in an agent might achieve 98% accuracy on training queries but misroute half of real user messages. An underfit model might default to a single intent regardless of input. Both failure modes degrade agent reliability without obvious error signals during development if evaluation splits are not used correctly."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LLM fine-tuning is also susceptible: overfitting to a small SFT dataset produces a model that recites training examples rather than generalizing instruction-following behavior."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 2 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "Benefits of understanding the bias-variance trade-off" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Framing overfitting and underfitting through the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "bias-variance trade-off",
            "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " provides a systematic way to diagnose and fix model performance:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "High bias (underfitting)",
                    "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — the model makes oversimplified assumptions; both training and validation error are high"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "High variance (overfitting)",
                    "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — the model is too sensitive to training data; training error is low but validation error is high"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 2 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "Trade-offs" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Increasing model complexity reduces bias but increases variance. There is no free lunch — the optimal model complexity depends on the amount and quality of available data. More data allows more complex models without overfitting; less data requires simpler models or stronger regularization."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 2 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "How it works" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 3 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "Detecting overfitting" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Plot training and validation loss (or accuracy) across epochs. In overfitting, training loss continues to decrease while validation loss starts increasing — the divergence point indicates where the model began memorizing noise."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 3 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "Detecting underfitting" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Both training and validation metrics plateau at a poor level early in training. The model has converged but never achieved good performance because it lacks sufficient capacity or features."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 3 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "Remedies for overfitting" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Regularization",
                    "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — add penalty terms (L1, L2) to the loss function to constrain parameter magnitude"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Early stopping",
                    "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — halt training when validation performance stops improving"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Dropout",
                    "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — randomly disable neurons during training to prevent co-adaptation"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "More training data",
                    "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — additional examples dilute the influence of noise"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Data augmentation",
                    "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — create synthetic variations of existing examples"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Reduce model complexity",
                    "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — fewer parameters, shallower architecture, or simpler algorithm"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 3 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "Remedies for underfitting" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Increase model complexity",
                    "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — more layers, more parameters, or a more expressive algorithm"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Add relevant features",
                    "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — the model may lack the inputs needed to capture the pattern"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Train longer",
                    "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — the model may not have converged yet"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Reduce regularization",
                    "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — excessive penalties may be preventing the model from learning"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 2 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "Examples" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Demonstrating overfitting with polynomial regression — a high-degree polynomial fits training noise:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": { "language": "python" },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\nfrom sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures\nfrom sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression\nfrom sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\nfrom sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error\n\nnp.random.seed(42)\nX = np.sort(np.random.rand(50, 1) * 10, axis=0)\ny = np.sin(X).ravel() + np.random.randn(50) * 0.3\n\nX_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(\n    X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42\n)\n\nfor degree in [1, 4, 15]:\n    poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree)\n    X_train_poly = poly.fit_transform(X_train)\n    X_test_poly = poly.transform(X_test)\n\n    model = LinearRegression()\n    model.fit(X_train_poly, y_train)\n\n    train_mse = mean_squared_error(y_train, model.predict(X_train_poly))\n    test_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, model.predict(X_test_poly))\n    print(f\"Degree {degree:2d} | Train MSE: {train_mse:.4f} | Test MSE: {test_mse:.4f}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Degree 1 underfits (high error on both sets). Degree 4 generalizes well. Degree 15 overfits (low train error, high test error)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Applying regularization to combat overfitting:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": { "language": "python" },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from sklearn.linear_model import Ridge\n\npoly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=15)\nX_train_poly = poly.fit_transform(X_train)\nX_test_poly = poly.transform(X_test)\n\nfor alpha in [0.0, 1.0, 100.0]:\n    model = Ridge(alpha=alpha)\n    model.fit(X_train_poly, y_train)\n\n    train_mse = mean_squared_error(y_train, model.predict(X_train_poly))\n    test_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, model.predict(X_test_poly))\n    print(f\"Alpha {alpha:6.1f} | Train MSE: {train_mse:.4f} | Test MSE: {test_mse:.4f}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 3 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "Overfitting in LLM fine-tuning" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When fine-tuning an LLM on a small instruction dataset, overfitting manifests as the model reproducing training examples verbatim rather than following the general instruction format. Mitigations include:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Limiting the number of fine-tuning epochs (early stopping on validation loss)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Using a lower learning rate to make smaller weight updates"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Expanding the fine-tuning dataset with diverse prompt variations"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Applying LoRA or other parameter-efficient methods that update fewer weights"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 2 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "Common mistakes" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Judging model quality on training metrics alone",
                    "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — high training accuracy can mask severe overfitting"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Adding complexity when underfitting without checking data quality first",
                    "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — sometimes the features simply do not contain the needed signal"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Over-regularizing",
                    "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — applying too much regularization turns an overfitting problem into an underfitting one"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Ignoring the learning curve",
                    "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — training and validation curves together reveal the diagnosis; a single metric snapshot does not"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 2 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "Best practices" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Always plot training and validation metrics side by side during training"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Use early stopping with a patience threshold to automatically halt at the optimal epoch"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Start with a simple model and increase complexity only when validation performance justifies it"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Collect more diverse training data before reaching for a more complex architecture"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "For LLM fine-tuning, monitor validation perplexity and test with held-out prompts not seen during training"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 2 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "Mental model" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Imagine fitting a curve through data points on a graph. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Underfitting",
            "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is drawing a straight line through clearly curved data — too simple. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Overfitting",
            "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is drawing a wiggly line that passes through every single point — including random scatter — and will miss new points entirely. The right model draws a smooth curve that follows the general trend without chasing noise."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 2 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "Key takeaways" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Overfitting: low training error, high validation error — the model memorized noise"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Underfitting: high error on both training and validation — the model is too simple"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Regularization, early stopping, more data, and simpler models address overfitting"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "More complexity, better features, and longer training address underfitting"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Training vs. validation learning curves are the primary diagnostic tool for both failure modes"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
